840abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"09 07:29:20Z):\n   EXAMPLE 2: Workflow with for-each loop and call of another workflow \n The following workflow is provided here to demonstrate the looping mechanism and the ability to call one workflow from another. \n Here is what the entire workflow looks like: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2ca4b43ee0aa38977a254d8d68935306eed80e58.png]\nDescription: The image illustrates a flowchart for the process titled \u0022Allotment_Update.\u0022 It begins with a \u0022Start\u0022 node and branches into a main section labeled \u00220050_For_each_Service,\u0022 which contains three sequential operations: \u00220100_LoadData_Allotment,\u0022 \u00220200_Transform_Allotment,\u0022 and \u00220300_StoreData_Allotment.\u0022 Following these operations, there is a process labeled \u00220400_Call_ServiceBlock_Create,\u0022 leading to an \u0022End\u0022 node. Additional elements depicted include \u0022InputData\u0022 and \u0022Allotment,\u0022 highlighting the inputs and outputs of the workflow. The apparent purpose of this diagram is to outline the steps involved in updating allotment data for various services.\n\n\n  \n   For-each loop \n The for-each command \u2013  (Block) For-each  \u2013 is used for the loop here. It executes a sequence for each occurrence of a specific element in the data; in this example, individual elements in  ROOT/services  ( IteratorXPath  property). That is, for each record there, the entire Load / Transform / Store sequence listed in steps 0100 through 0300 is performed. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7e5cd96a8253bc89a856c446473d00222e7d3aea.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface component, likely from a development or programming environment, showcasing a list of tasks and blocks. The visible items include: (Task) Service Method Call, (Task) User Interface, (Task) Workflow Call, (Task) Set Workflow Property, (Task) Update context by Xpath, (Task) Accept Context Store Changes, (Block) Transaction, (Block) For-each (highlighted), (Block) Loop, (Task) Check Rule, and (Task) Wait. The purpose of this interface appears to be to manage or configure workflow elements, with a focus on organizing various tasks and control structures in a programming or automation context.\n\n\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f1daae66d6a323f56b9840abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a programming or configuration environment, specifically focused on a block labeled \u00220050_For-each_Service.\u0022 It contains sections for \u0022Info\u0022 and \u0022Error Handling.\u0022 The \u0022Info\u0022 section includes the fields \u0022Ancestors\u0022 set to \u0022False,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable\u0022 set to \u0022False,\u0022 and \u0022Name\u0022 also set to \u00220050_For-each_Service.\u0022 In the \u0022Error Handling\u0022 section, the \u0022OnFailure\u0022 field is set to \u0022WorkflowFails.\u0022 The \u0022Misc\u0022 section includes three parameters: \u0022IgnoreSourceContextChanges\u0022 set to \u0022True,\u0022 \u0022IteratorXPath\u0022 with the value \u0022/ROOT/services,\u0022 and \u0022SourceContextStore\u0022 leading to an \u0022Input Data\u0022 field. This appears to facilitate configuration settings for processing services in a workflow.\n\n\n  \n   Context Store of the Loop \n It is also worth noting that this loop first retrieves data from the \u201Cexternal\u201D context store  InputData  and then uses its own \u201Cinternal\u201D context store, named  Allotment , during its execution. This context store is therefore intended only for this specific block. \n   Calling Another Workflow \n In step 0400, the workflow calls another workflow, which is a  Workflow call (Task)  type, and subsequently passes the necessary data to it via the  OutputContextStore . The output has no further use within this workflow, so the  Output Method  is set to  Ignore . \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png]\nDescription: The image displays a UI for a workflow call labeled \u00220400_Call_ServiceBlock_Create\u0022 within a task management or workflow designer tool. The interface includes sections such as Info: with schema items like \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 the latter explicitly showing \u00220400_Call_ServiceBlock_Create.\u0022 Under \u0022Error Handling,\u0022 there\u0027s an option for \u0022OnFailure\u0022 set to \u0022WorkflowFails.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.0018643709,0.0039797677,-0.06986403,0.04148951,0.014080839,-0.038012363,0.0082050925,0.017646952,-0.0108757,-0.00797709,0.017397514,-0.025424674,-0.009851183,0.025117958,0.029852236,-0.0017912596,0.005050091,0.018458659,-0.0078702625,0.020552207,0.0034768665,0.01765588,0.06514901,0.048879668,0.0006802992,0.010254141,-0.013021623,-0.049650278,0.0005787192,0.02309725,0.024431542,0.0044076974,-0.015691323,-0.035807956,0.0006188429,-0.010854342,0.016199365,0.0023316008,-0.04227755,0.043897025,0.001005584,0.014729536,-0.0034425175,-0.015006393,0.0071002934,-0.0015759387,-0.024302142,-0.023449942,0.00010473237,-0.031588428,-0.043189064,0.00035749972,0.028590003,-0.014218576,0.03189631,0.044530798,-0.028736895,-0.014241587,-0.099127695,0.030328557,-0.012127856,0.0022656044,-0.014139388,0.0037643185,-0.030002082,0.041897863,-0.018688673,0.017145243,-0.009588772,0.017807303,-0.0024848175,0.012384503,-0.06393608,-0.020721626,-0.024102